    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. I want to make sure they really understand why this is so important though. Some people argue that this is just a way for judges to make up new rights that aren't actually in the Constitution. How should I explain to my students why the \"substantive\" part is actually more legitimate than just sticking to the literal text?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"substantive\" aspect is crucial because the Constitution's original wording only protected specific rights written there, while the full scope of liberty requires protecting unlisted human rights. This concept acknowledges that the written law is a static document, yet human life and evolving society demand constant interpretation of what those rights actually mean in practice. By basing decisions on enduring principles of fairness and justice found in Western tradition, rather than just changing every word of the text, substantive due process offers a stable method for courts to shield individuals from government overreach without needing to rewrite the Constitution for every new right.",
      "source": "target",
